To: 78tools
Fcc: outbox
Subject: New d78 command, changes to the logical address mapping feature.
-------

There is a new command, "pmap" that displays a character for every
4k page in simulated physical memory.  

  '.' means the page hasn't been touched
  'D' means the page has been touched
  'I' means the page has been touched and at least one instruction
      has been executed on it

There's an example of the output of this command at the end of this
mail after running the UTek kernel through some initialization.

----------------------------------------------------------

Paulg pointed out that dbx already had a variable to control the
mapping of kernel addresses.  So the d78 environment variable that
was "$logical" is now "$mapaddr" and the -k option should work.

All of the s78, d78, and min files that implement these changes
are checked in for those of you that build your own d78's.

----------------------------------------------------------

There is a very new version of the GH 88000 C compiler on cupcake
in /UTek/tools/lib78/GHcomp.new.  GHcomp is a symbolic link
to GHcomp.new, switch it back to GHcomp.old if you need to.

d78 does not understand the code generated by the GH compiler,
so some things, like stack backtraces, misbehave.  When I figure
out what it is that GH is generating, I'll update d78 to be
able to handle both GH and Moto-generated code.

----------------------------------------------------------

The output of the pmap command after running the UTek kernel to
the "panic: iinit" point:

